## Overview
Create the canonical, project-wide Decisions List / Content Browser for Archject that presents every decision in a clear, organized, and actionable way. The page supports robust filters, bulk actions (share links, export, change status), quick previews, and seamless integration with the surrounding decision workflow (CRUD, templates, and dashboards). It should be visually consistent with the project’s design system, accessible, mobile-friendly, and scalable to handle large project ecosystems with multiple decisions, documents, and comments.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A central, canonical list of all decisions across a project, presented as a searchable, filterable, and bulk-action-enabled content browser. Each decision is a self-contained object with metadata, options, status, due dates, associated files, comments, and client-facing share links.

Goals:
- Provide fast, full-text search and faceted filters across projects, decisions, files, and comments.
- Enable bulk actions: share client links, export decision data (PDF/CSV/JSON), and bulk status changes (e.g., move multiple decisions from draft to pending or approved).
- Offer quick preview: hover or select a decision to view essential details (summary, options, status, due date, linked files, client link, recent activity) without navigating away.
- Promote faster decision creation via templates and an integrated Create button that leverages the Decision Templates Library.
- Maintain an audit-friendly, time-stamped history and linkage to the Edit / Manage Decision Page for deep editing and versioning.

Connected features:
- Search & Filter Functionality: Full-text search across decisions, projects, files, and comments; faceted filters by status, assignee, date ranges, template type, priority, requester/client status, and tags.
- Decision Objects CRUD: Create, read, update, delete Decision Objects, including options, metadata, and status transitions (draft, pending, approved, rejected). Include per-decision history, change tracking, and versioning hooks for re-issues.
- Decision Templates Library: Library of opinionated templates for common decision types (finishes, layouts, change requests) to accelerate decision creation with pre-filled options, metadata fields, and default status transitions.

UI elements and how they need to look:
- Filter Bar: status (tags), assignee, date range, template type, search box with autosuggest; quick filters for “My Decisions,” “Awaiting Client,” and “Overdue.”
- Decisions Table/Card: per-row or per-card representation showing title, status badge, due date, linked files count, client share link icon, last updated timestamp, and quick action row (edit, duplicate, delete, share).
- Bulk Actions Bar: appears when one or more items are selected; options include Export, Share Links, Change Status, Assign, Remove, and Delete (with confirm).
- Preview Pane: floating or docked pane that shows a quick view of the selected decision with sections for Summary, Key Options, Metadata, Activity, and a link to Open in Manage/Edit page.
- Create Decision Button: prominent, pill-shaped primary action, opening a modal or side panel to create a decision (with metadata, options, and initial status).
- Templates Quick Insert: a panel or dropdown to apply templates during create or via the editor.
- Client Share Links: indicator/icon per decision with copy/share actions and link status (active/expired).

Visual guidance:
- Use the project’s design system: clean white cards, soft shadows, 12–16px radii, ample whitespace, and gentle color accents for statuses. Primary actions use deep green (#195C4A). Success indicators use bright green (#7BE495). Warnings use yellow/orange tones; errors use light red. All typography adheres to the standardized font family and weights.

Connected Pages:
- Dashboard: User-specific overview with decisions awaiting client response and quick actions to create or share client links.
- Edit / Manage Decision Page: Detailed editing with history, version comparison, and reissue share link capability.

API integrations:
- No external APIs required for this task; all data interactions will be via the project’s internal API surface.

## Components to Build
- DecisionsListContainer: Grid/list wrapper for responsive rendering, handles pagination, virtualized scrolling for large datasets.
- FilterBar: UI for text search, multi-selects, range pickers, and quick filters; emits filter state to parent.
- DecisionsTable/Card: Card-based or tabular representation with responsive columns; includes status badge, due date, counts, and action icons.
- PreviewPane: Read-only quick view or interactive mini-editor for summary and metadata; supports hover/selection triggers.
- BulkActionsBar: Top/side bar that enables bulk operations; includes confirm dialogs for destructive actions.
- CreateDecisionModal / CreateDecisionPanel: Form-based creation surface with validation, supports templates integration.
- EditDecisionPageLink: Route or button to navigate to the dedicated Edit / Manage Decision Page.
- TemplatesLibraryPanel: Browse and apply templates; supports searching, filtering, and “Apply template” action.
- ShareLinkManager: UI and logic to generate, copy, and manage client-facing share links (active/expired).
- HistoryPanel: Lightweight view of decision history within the Edit page; for the list view, show last activity snippet.

Technical details for components:
- Each component should be designed with accessibility (A11y) in mind: proper roles, keyboard navigation, ARIA labels, and screen-reader friendly labels.
- State management: Use a centralized store (Redux/Context) or a modern hook-based approach with a clear schema for decisions, templates, filters, and UI state (loading, error, success).

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Build responsive UI following the design system:
  - Desktop: Two-column layout with a left filter panel and right content area, plus a persistent preview pane.
  - Tablet/Mobile: Collapsible filter bar, card/list list with full-width rows, bottom sheet or modal for create/edit.
- Components should be reusable across the app:
  - Button, Tag/Status, Card, TableRow, Modal, Drawer/Panel, Input, Select, MultiSelect, DateRangePicker, IconButton.
- Interactions:
  - Debounced full-text search; apply filters with a single-click or “Enter” for search.
  - Bulk selection via checkbox in each row; “Select All” in paginated view.
  - Sortable columns in table view and equivalent options in card view (by last updated, due date, status, title).
  - Quick preview on hover or selection; optional pinned preview pane for focus.
- Templates integration:
  - When creating a decision, user can pick a template type (finishes, layouts, change requests) and pre-fill fields.
- Data visualization placeholders:
  - If charts or trend indicators exist on the page (e.g., decisions over time), provide minimal, consistent chart components or placeholders aligned with the design system.

### Backend
- API surface (internal to Archject; ensure endpoints are RESTful or GraphQL-based per project standards):
  - GET /projects/{projectId}/decisions: list with filtering, search, pagination, sorting.
  - POST /projects/{projectId}/decisions: create decision; supports initial options, metadata, status.
  - GET /projects/{projectId}/decisions/{decisionId}: fetch single for quick preview.
  - PATCH /projects/{projectId}/decisions/{decisionId}: update fields, options, metadata, status transitions.
  - DELETE /projects/{projectId}/decisions/{decisionId}: delete decision.
  - POST /projects/{projectId}/decisions/bulk/export: export selected decisions to PDF/CSV/JSON.
  - POST /projects/{projectId}/decisions/bulk/share: generate share links for selected decisions.
  - POST /projects/{projectId}/decisions/bulk/change-status: bulk status update.
  - GET /decision-templates: list templates; GET /decision-templates/{templateId}: details.
  - POST /projects/{projectId}/decisions/{decisionId}/clone: duplicate decision.
- Database tables (conceptual):
  - decisions: id, project_id, title, status (draft/pending/approved/rejected), due_date, assignee_id, template_id, summary, metadata JSON, options JSON, shared_link JSON, created_at, updated_at.
  - decision_options: id, decision_id, option_key, option_value, metadata JSON.
  - decision_history: id, decision_id, action, changed_by, changed_at, diff JSON.
  - decision_files: id, decision_id, file_id, relation_type (attachment, drawing, spec).
  - templates: id, type (finishes/layouts/change_request), name, description, default_options JSON, metadata JSON.
  - share_links: id, decision_id, url, expires_at, status (active/expired).
  - comments: id, decision_id, user_id, content, created_at, updated_at.
- Validation:
  - Business rules for status transitions (e.g., draft -> pending -> approved/rejected; cannot move from approved to draft without explicit action).
  - Metadata and options schema validation per decision type/template.
  - Ensure foreign keys and referential integrity for related entities (files, comments, history).
  - Input validation on create/update: required fields (title, status at minimum), length constraints, and proper date formats.

### Integration
- State synchronization:
  - The DecisionsList page must reflect real-time or near real-time changes from other editors (use WebSocket or long-polling where available; fallback to periodic polling).
- Cross-page consistency:
  - Creating/editing a decision should immediately reflect in the list and update the preview pane.
  - Templates library must sync with Create decision flow and persist chosen templates to the decision record.
- Access control:
  - Ensure users can view decisions for projects they have access to; enforce permissions on CRUD, bulk actions, and sharing.

## User Experience Flow
1. User lands on Decisions List / Content Browser for a project.
2. Page loads with a canonical list of decisions, showing key fields (title, status badge, due date, files count, last updated, and client link status).
3. User uses the Filter Bar:
   - Types a search query; selects one or more statuses; filters by assignee; chooses a date range; optionally filters by template type.
   - Results update in real-time; the user can sort by title, due date, last updated.
4. User selects one or more decisions via checkboxes:
   - Bulk Actions Bar becomes active (Export, Share Links, Change Status, Assign, Delete).
   - User can export to PDF/CSV/JSON or generate share links for all selected decisions.
   - User can bulk-change status (e.g., draft -> pending) with confirmation.
5. User clicks on a decision (or hovers to see a quick preview):
   - Preview Pane displays decision summary, key options, metadata, and recent activity.
   - User can click to “Open in Edit / Manage Decision Page” for full editing; from there, changes are versioned and history is available.
6. User uses Create Decision:
   - Click Create Decision; a modal/side panel opens.
   - User fills in title, selects a template type (finishes/layout/change_request) to prefill fields, adds options and metadata, assigns to a teammate, sets initial status.
   - Upon save, decision appears in the list, and a share link may be generated.
7. User navigates to Templates Library:
   - Browse templates, preview, and apply to a new decision or as a starting point for an existing one.
8. Both the Dashboard and Edit / Manage Decision Page interoperate:
   - Dashboard shows “Decisions awaiting client response” and “Recent activity”; actions from the list surface here.
   - Edit page provides deeper editing with history, version comparison, and reissue share link.

