  - Ensure users can view decisions for projects they have access to; enforce permissions on CRUD, bulk actions, and sharing.

## User Experience Flow
1. User lands on Decisions List / Content Browser for a project.
2. Page loads with a canonical list of decisions, showing key fields (title, status badge, due date, files count, last updated, and client link status).
3. User uses the Filter Bar:
   - Types a search query; selects one or more statuses; filters by assignee; chooses a date range; optionally filters by template type.
   - Results update in real-time; the user can sort by title, due date, last updated.
4. User selects one or more decisions via checkboxes:
   - Bulk Actions Bar becomes active (Export, Share Links, Change Status, Assign, Delete).
   - User can export to PDF/CSV/JSON or generate share links for all selected decisions.
   - User can bulk-change status (e.g., draft -> pending) with confirmation.
5. User clicks on a decision (or hovers to see a quick preview):
   - Preview Pane displays decision summary, key options, metadata, and recent activity.
   - User can click to “Open in Edit / Manage Decision Page” for full editing; from there, changes are versioned and history is available.
6. User uses Create Decision:
   - Click Create Decision; a modal/side panel opens.
   - User fills in title, selects a template type (finishes/layout/change_request) to prefill fields, adds options and metadata, assigns to a teammate, sets initial status.
   - Upon save, decision appears in the list, and a share link may be generated.
7. User navigates to Templates Library:
   - Browse templates, preview, and apply to a new decision or as a starting point for an existing one.
8. Both the Dashboard and Edit / Manage Decision Page interoperate:
   - Dashboard shows “Decisions awaiting client response” and “Recent activity”; actions from the list surface here.
   - Edit page provides deeper editing with history, version comparison, and reissue share link.

